{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_janeway_ver01/data/sn87055779/00416150862/1930091501/0560.xml":{"full_text":"<r''\nr\nINDUSTRY SPEEDS\nFALL BUSINESS IN\nEMPLOYING HELP\nManufactured Goods Find\nrfi\nDemand; Factories\nRehiring Workers. i\nBy RICHARD L. QRIDLET\nt) t United Press Financial Writer\nNEW YORK, Sept. IV\u2014Possibilities\nof a business revival ot more than\nr.\u2022 seasonal proportions this fan was\nseen this week in reports from nearly\nevery section of the country that faev\ntories were rehiring workers on a\nlarge scale to supply the demand for\nmanufactured products.\nRetail merchants who have allowed\ntheir inventories to drop to danger\niously low levels are making frantic\nefforts to replenish their stocks in\n|s\u2018 anticipation of the late September\nSH buying movement and many whole\nsalers and makers are increasing their\nforces to meet rush demands.\nftV Railroad car loadings have risen to\n-S the highest levels since the start of\nthe current year, indicating the great\nly Increased distribution of goods\nover the past few weeks; steel pro\nduction has made further gains and\nvarious other indices of trade are\nshowing more than the seasonal in\ncrease expected at this time.\n\u2022nie week brought its usual drop\nof optimistic business forecasts by\nimportant economists, bankers and\nindustrialists, accompanied by signs\nof greater public participation in the\nstock market\nConcrete evidence ot the extent of\nthe revival from the summer let\ndown was continued in reports from\nvarious retail channels. Many stores\nreport a loosening of buyers\u2019 purse\nstring, while heavy theater attendance\nis believed to indicate continued large\npurchasing power of the general pub\nlic. New York bank deposits con\ntinued to show good gains over a\nM. year ago.\nThe unemployment situation still\nis considered unsatisfactory but em\nployment agencies in widely separated\nsections of the country report an in\ncreased inquiry for the more skilled\nworkers. Conditions in the auto in\ndustry continued poor but many of\nthe leading radio companies are in\ncreasing production.\nThe belief is still stressed however,\nthat continued improvement is busi\nness will be market by unsettlement\nin many lines. The building industry,\nfor example, continues in the throes\nof a depression. Nevertheless, a\ngradual reduction of unemployment\nis expected over the next few months.\nHOOVER CLASHES\nWITH NAVY MEN\n2$;.\n'2\n*.fv\n;is v\n\n\n'if' V:\ni\nBuilding Program Work\nMay Prove to be Heat\ned Contest.\nBy International N\u00ab\u00abi Service:\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 14.\u2014A con\ntest loomed today between the Hoov\ner administration and the \u201cold line\u201d\nadmirals of the navy in framing a\nbuilding program under the London\ntreaty as well as providing a budget\nfor the next year, following an\nnouncement that Admiral William\nV. Pratt would become chief of naval\noperations Sept. 18.\nThe action of the .administration\nin relieving Admiral Charles F.\nHughes a month before Pratt was\nscheduled to take office was regarded\nas notice the administration expects\nto dictate the navy\u2019s future building\npolicy.\nAdmiral Pratt, an adviser at the\nLondon naval conference, stood al\nmost alone among the admirals in\nendorsing the naval limitation treaty.\nHis selection by President Hoover to\nhead the navy came after the con\nference.\n\"FLETCHER IS READY\nTO WORK ON TARIFF\nBy International New* Service:\nGREENCASTLE, Pa., Sept. 14.\u2014\nHenry P. Fletcher, chairman of the\nrecently organized tariff commission,\nwill go to Washington early next\nweek to assume his duties, he told-In\nternational News Service here today,\nbut he' has had no communication\nfrom President' Hoover regarding a\nsurvey of schedules affecting Canada.\n\u201cI will probably go to Washington\nTuesday,\u201d Fletcher said, \u201cand I pre\nsume the members of the new com\nmission will be sworn in Tuesday or\nWednesday.\n\u201cI have heard nothing from Wash\nington concerning a survey of tariff\nschedules affecting the Dominion of\nCanada, but I think it likely that such\na survey will be made after the new\ncommission is organized, which* may\ntake two or three days.\u201d\nSTOLEN CAR FOUND\nIN INDIANAPOLIS\nA Ford coupe owned by Grace ott.\nstolen here 62 days ago. was found\nFriday in Indianapolis, parked in\nfront of the home of Thomas Utter\nback.\nThe automobile was recovered in\nDetective M. B. Corbin of the Indi\nanapolis police force, and Utterback\nwas locked up in the Indianapolis\nciyt Jail on a charge of vehicle taking.\nHe will be given a hearing next\nweek to determine whether he will be\nreturned here for trial.\nCLEVERLY HIDDEN\nBOOZE VATS FOUND\nBy International New* Service:\nINDIANAPOLIS. Sept. 14.\u2014Seven\ningeniously concealed liquor vats\nwere found by police in the home ot\nJoe fDusty) Sawyer here, they said\nSaturday. After emptying them of\nalcohol and whisky, the officers ar\nrested Sawyer and his housekeeper\nMrs. Erol Meeker. 39, on blind tiger\nchargee.\nOne vat was hidden in the wail\nover a hall doorway, another in a\nstairway entered by raising a spindle\nin (he rail, a cleverly arranged valve\nopened another vat placed behind\nthe kitchen sink, one waa concealed\nbehind a picture of \u201cSeptember\nMorn\u201d in the bathroom, two were\nbeneath counters In an annex to\nSawyer\u2019s poolroom adjoining the\nhouse and one ras under a rug on\nthe floor of thy living goon. i\nSocieties Pledge\nLocal Students\nAt State School\ni\nImHiI U' Thf\nBLOOMINGTON. Ind., Sept. 14.\n\u2014Several South Bend and northern\nIndiana students at the University ot\nIndiana are among those pledged to\nfraternities and sororities during\ntheir week on the campus.\nThe letter organizations and the\nstudents they have pledged include:\nPhi Mu. Ula Allen; Sigma Kappa.\nPat Hilliard. Geraldine Hatt, Dorothy\nMarcus; Alpha Omicron Pi, Yefcive\nBrowne; Alpha Chi Omega, Susan\nBorden; Theta Chi. Charles Lundin;\nDelta Up6llon, Alexis Bams; Sigma\nChi, John Boone, Robert Zorn; Alpha\nEpsilon, Albert Altfeld; Delta Tau\nDelta, Kenneth Erhardt, William\nHillman; Delta Phi Sigma, George\nColip, Mishawaka; Alpha Omicron\nPi. Violet Debow; Phi Mu, Carol Cle\nment, Peail Parvis, Rose Rohleder,\nElkhart; Chi Omega, Virginia Adams;\nKappa Delta, Jean Shinneman; Al\npha Chi Omega, Harriet Shrelnder;\nSigma Chi, James Fetters, Michigan\nCity; Sigma Pi, Carl Heading; Sigma\nAlpha Epsilon, Jack Cathcart, Earl\nCalvert, Dicjc Cook; Phi Delta Theta,\nEarl Colpltts, Goshen; Sigma Kappa,\nWava Tyler; Delta Gamma, Barbara\nDow, Susan Yoder; Kappa Alpha1\nTheta, Laura Kidler, Betty Stodl; j\nBeta Theta Pi, Jack Shannahan; Phi\nKappa Psi, Robert Swanberg; Delta\nUpsilon, Edward Angelmeyer and\nWilliam Stuckm&n.\nNAME SCHROEDER\nIN TRUE BILLS\n\nMurder Suspect Indicted j\nBy Marion County j\nGrand Jury.\nBy I slfrt Prfds: i\nINDIANAPOLIS, Sept. 14.\u2014Harold\nHerbert Schrceder of Mobile, Ala.,\nwas Indicted today by the Marion\ncounty, Ind., grand jury, on three\ncounts, charging first degree murder.\nSchroeder is charged with the\ndeath of an unidentified man whose\nbody was found in Schroeder\u2019s auto\non a highway near Indianapolis last\nMay 31. Both the body and the auto\nwere reduced almost to ashes in the\nfire which the defendant has admit\nted he started.\nSchroeder has contended that the\nvictim was a hitch-hiker who was\nkilled when the auto ran into a ditch\nnear ,Terre Haute, and that he burn\ned the machine and body because he\nfeared a murder charge.\nThe indictment charges Schroeder\nwith killing the man by stabbing\nburning, and \"methods unknown.\u201d\nThe defendant has been in Marion\ncounty jail since soon after his cap\nture in Mobile last June.\nBLAME WALL STREET\nIN, BUSINESS SLUMP\nBy International Kem Service:\nGENEVA, Sept. 14.\u2014Responsibility\nfor the world-wide depression and un\nemployment was laid squarely on the\nshoulders of Wall street today at the\nassembly of the League of Nations.\nWilliam Graham, president of the\nBritish board of trade and league\ndelegate, declared that the \u201cgeneral\neconomic chaos\u201d followed the Wail\nstreet stock market crash last fall. He\ndemanded that the.league seek a rem\nedy for \u201cthe economic nationalism\u201d\nwhich, he held, has. sprung'up every\nwhere since the war.\nA heavy blow was dealt Aristide\nBriand\u2019s European federation propos\nal by the Swiss delegate Motta, who\nmaintained he saw no practical pur\npose in it. He suggested that the\nschepie be handed to a sub-commit\ntee of the league,-which-he said was\n\u201cfully equipped to! carry'it out.\u201d\nFORSYTHE HELD IN\nLING LE1N0UIRY\nState\u2019s Attorney\u2019s Office\nWill Question Man\nIn Mlirder.\n\nBy International News Smlwj\nCHICAGO, Sept. 14.\u2014\u201cRed\u201d For\nsythe, sought for questioning in the\nmurder of Alfred \u201cJake\u201d Lingle, Chi\ncago Tribune reporter, is in custody\nof the state's attorney\u2019s office, ac\ncording to a report that was given\nwide credence today.\nForsythe, it is said, has been held\nincommunicado since last Tuesday.\nCredence was given the report\nsinoe neither Pat Roche nor Charles\nRathbun, In charge of the Lingle\ninvestigation could be located for ver\nification.\nJames M. Burke, attorney for For\nsythe, offered under certain condi\ntions, to surrender Forsythe earlier\nin the week. Roche and Rathbun.\nhowever, refused. to dicker with the\nattorney and demanded Forsythe\nsurrender without any qualifications.\nHIGHWAY OFFICIALS\nSETTLE BRIDGE ROW\nBy r\u00abl*fd Pr*(\u00ab:\nINDIANAPOLIS, Sept. 14.\u2014All de\ntails relative to construction of a\n$4000.000 bridge between Evansville,\nInd., and Henderson, Ky., were Ironed\nout at a meeting of highway officials\nof the state in Louisville, Friday,\nand work will commence as soon as\npossible. Indiana officials announced\nupon their return from the confer\nence.\nKentucky officials agreed to pro\nvide money by bonds to take care of\ntheir $2,000,00 portion of the cost.\nDelay had been occasioned by Indi\nana's refusal to go ahead with con\nstruction plans under 'the financing\narrangement previously made by\nKentucky.\nDOG\u2019S \u2018TESTIMONY5\nWINS COURT BATTLE\nBy CnlM Fret*:\nMINNEAPOLIS, Minn., Sept .1$.\u2014\nWhen Ben Stillman entered court to\nfight a $75 damage suit which Morris\nEpstein filed against him on the\nclaim Stillman\u2019s dog bad bitten Ep\nstein, he took the dog as his star\nwitness. The judge dismissed the case\nwhen Stillmfn showed that the dog\nhad no teeth.\ncomics\nSKIPPY\n\nweu, ive tried Mr bcamedcst to make\nvest*' street see that the jAc*mviTi\u00a3r(\nOF SPUMONC Ape HURTING THE 06C6NT\nPeople UNcess A COOPLC Of rotten APPCEJ*.\nAP\u20ac TAKEN OUT OF XHB \u00a9ARREt-ACC THC f\nAPPc\u20ac5 u;iu so on cer rotten, y\u2014\u2014i\nr\nV.>.\n,y.\n.t i- y\nr\nA#\n\nIfc?\n\nis\n**v\nrJWHfN I TRY TO POfNr THESE\nOtSCoST FUC TWINES OUT ro PEOPLE,\nthey calc we a jacketeer instead]\nOf 6\u20acN0\u00bbN* A HAND \u00ab5oi* W6 Can\nCCtAN 7^6 GANGSTERS OUT OF\nV6S\u20acY STREET\u2014 ONCC An' FOR\nVAw.ic\n\nI\":,-;/\nir\nBy PERCY CROSBY\ni.\nI''\n\nvooRseR than acc is that ir\nBelittles nice (pRt* an'when\nTHeY'R\u20ac CHEAPENED CuHAr'j r\u00ab6\nSFNJE Or civil** FWClt, 1\nSAY \\S THAT iry\nA TERR IBC\u20ac\nsTOCtf IN THC\nNose AT\nRomance\n<7/5\n1930 Percy L Crosby. Great BriUin rights reserved\nI King Feature* Syndicate. Inc.\nr\nTOOTS AND CASPER\nSi\n\u25a0'\u2022iS\n\n\u00bbi\nBy J. MURPHY\nj\nSiV-5\nDUMB DORA\nBy PAUL FUNG\nt\nMISS ONA MtLVUN.\nVOUR FIANCEE,\nON THE \u2018PHONE N\nSir*\nHER\nI'M OUT\nBUSV\u2014\u25a0\nanvthincs\n1 s\nTHIS tS A. BUST DAV POP VOU,\nSIR* THIS IS THE DAV THE N\nI MTES NATIONAL. BANKERS ARE\nCOMING TO SEE VOU REGARDING\nFRECKLES AND HIS FRIENDS\nYOU PRO 8ASUY LOST\nTHAT BOX OP GCU8\nPRON\\ TVlg PLAUe\n\\HHEN NtoO DIO THOSE\nfancy didoes spore\nYOU kMEMJ X MJAS\nIN THE PLANS\n\\MITU VoO..\nEECRON WEBBS X\ndi